I want to tell you all about something I’m really excited about—it’s called the Voyager Scholarship. I’ve met so many young people who are interested in public service, but are worried about how they’re going to pay for school. They’re wondering how they can afford to go to school while broadening their experiences and seeing the world at the same time. 
 
So Barack and I wanted to help. That’s why we’re thrilled to be teaming up with Airbnb’s Brian Chesky to announce the Voyager Scholarship which will provide financial aid to support their education, expand their horizons, and access an incredible network of leaders and mentors to help young people on their journey to create change. 
 
The Voyager Scholarship is for rising juniors in college in the United States who are committed to making a positive impact—if that sounds like you, I hope you will apply today!

node.text:
Decades before our family lived there, First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt planted a Victory Garden on the White House lawn, and I'm thrilled to share that the Fruit & Vegetable Garden at the Obama Presidential Center will be named in her honor! Mrs. Roosevelt is our longest-serving First Lady, setting a towering standard for so many in our country and around the world, including me. I've always been inspired by her brilliance, her strength, and her remarkable advocacy for the causes she believed in.

The garden itself will be a nod to the White House Kitchen Garden that I planted in 2009, featuring a wide variety of accessible planting beds for seasonal fruits and vegetables. It will also include a picnic area, and Garden Classroom & Teaching Kitchen where visitors of all ages and abilities will be able to participate in hands-on workshops to learn how to grow, harvest, and prepare fresh food. This will be a space for folks on the South Side and visitors alike to come together, and I can’t wait for you all to see it!

node.text:
From an early age, my mom, Marian Robinson, fostered in me a deep sense of confidence in who I was and who I could be. She taught me how to think for myself, use my own voice, and understand my own worth. I simply wouldn’t be who I am today without her.

As we get ready for #MothersDay, I’m proud to announce that the “Opening the White House” exhibit in the Obama Presidential Center Museum will be named in her honor.

When the museum opens, this will be a place that welcomes folks from across the country and around the world, and thousands of families just like mine who live right down the street. Love you, Mom – thank you for being a guiding light in my life. 💕

This #WomensHistoryMonth, I’m thinking about the next generation of girls who are working to change our communities and make our world a better place. Last month, I met a few talented young women at the @ManoaHeritageCenter in Hawaiʻi who are doing just that. These middle and high school students have already started taking charge at an early age by leading robotics classes, teaching other young people about protecting the ocean, and expressing themselves through their art. 

Take a listen to our conversation with the @GirlsOpportunityAlliance—I know you’ll be as inspired by their stories as I am.

From riding bikes around our street and running around backyard barbecues to celebrating friends’ birthdays in the neighborhood—my brother @CraigMalRob and I have shared so many great memories from our time growing up on the South Side of Chicago.
 
Now, kids everywhere will get to hear stories from our childhood through my brother’s new Little Craig Series with @Vooks. He’s been working with Vooks to help inspire a love of reading in kids around the world, and I hope you’ll check out the first book in his series—Little Craig: Balloons and Cake by clicking the link in my bio. ❤️

The right to vote is under threat. There are people who are working day in and day out to make it harder for communities of color, people with disabilities, and young people to cast their ballots. With the 2022 midterm elections around the corner, we’ve got to do what we can to change that. 

That's why @whenweallvote is launching the #VoteLoud HBCU Squad Challenge with my When We All Vote Co-Chair, @cp3.

Our hope is that the Vote Loud HBCU Squad Challenge will empower HBCU students to take a leading role in mobilization efforts on their campuses by doing everything from hosting voter registration drives to educating others about what’s on the ballot, and more. 

Everyone—no matter their background or circumstance—should feel empowered to vote. So I hope you’ll join us by signing up at the link in my bio.

Happy National School Counseling Week to our nation’s incredible school counselors! 🎉
 
School counselors see the promise in each of their students and work tirelessly to help them be who they were truly meant to be. They are there for their students in their darkest moments, when they’re most anxious and afraid, and show them that they matter. And they do it all in the face of some overwhelming challenges and endless demands for their time—I couldn’t be more grateful for all that they do to transform the lives of our young people every day. 
 
This year’s 2022 School Counselor of the Year, Alma Lopez, is an example of a school counselor who goes above and beyond for her students. She’s the lead school counselor at Livingston Middle School in Livingston, California. Every morning, she welcomes her students by cheering them on as they walk into school—pom-poms and all—to show them that she is happy to see them. As a first-generation college graduate, she knows the power of higher education and empowers her middle school students to start thinking about their plans for the future. Every day, she inspires her students to become the best version of themselves. Congrats to the 2022 School Counselor of the Year, Alma Lopez! #ReachHigher 🎓

In 2020, during a global pandemic, Americans showed up in record numbers to exercise their right to vote. But these last couple of years, state legislatures across the country have passed laws making it harder for people to cast their ballots. The folks who want to derail our progress want us to stay quiet and stop paying attention.
 
But it doesn’t have to be this way. With your help, we can change the culture around voting and fight voter suppression. 
 
I hope you’ll join my co-chairs by getting involved with @WhenWeAllVote. Text “join” to 56005 to sign up and learn more.

On the day of my husband's second inauguration, 15-year-old Hadiya Pendleton came down to Washington and performed in the festivities with her majorette squad. A week later, this bright and beautiful girl was killed in a tragic shooting on the South Side of Chicago. 

I never had the chance to meet Hadiya while she was alive, but after she died, I was able to spend some time with her loved ones. I learned about how she was an honor student, how much she loved music, how she loved going out to get ice cream with her friends. And the more I heard, the more I understood the extraordinary potential inside of her—a potential that was stolen by the epidemic of gun violence. 

At Hadiya’s memorial service, her mom, Cleopatra, said something to me that has stayed with me ever since. She said: “I did everything I was supposed to.” 

I still think about Hadiya to this day. 

Barack and I are proud to honor her legacy through the Hadiya Pendleton Winter Garden at the Obama Presidential Center. We hope this garden can be a way to share her light with others and help young people – just like Hadiya – find their own place in the world, and build lives worthy of their dreams.

On this International #EducationDay, I’m thinking of the students out there who are working so hard to go to school, despite living in a world with so much uncertainty. 
 
Two years into the pandemic, children across the world continue to face school closures, obstacles to remote learning, and challenges both in and out of the classroom. Sadly, the pandemic isn’t the only barrier to education. Even before COVID-19, more than 98 million adolescent girls around the world were not in school. 
 
Judith was almost one of those girls. She grew up in a small village in Tanzania, and almost saw her dreams of an education end as a teenager, when she faced pressure to get married and drop out of school. But a scholarship from @AsanteAfrica, an organization we support through the @GirlsOpportunityAlliance, allowed her to keep chasing her dreams. Judith became the first woman in her community to attend university, and she isn’t stopping there. Today, she’s determined to help other girls in her village continue their education too.
 
Judith’s story embodies so much of what our work with the Girls Opportunity Alliance is all about—and shows that when we empower one girl, it can create a ripple effect across communities. So as we celebrate the Day of Education, I hope you’ll take action to support young women like Judith. Check out the link in my bio to see how you can make a difference in a girl’s life.

One of my favorite parts about writing Becoming and sharing my own story has been seeing how it relates to so many of yours. 
 
I recently spoke with a group of students from community colleges and universities across the country about the power of owning your unique story. I hope you’ll tune-in on Monday, 1/17 to watch our conversation on BET or BET HER at 7pm ET. 
 
I also wanted to give a special shout-out to the talented @YaraShahidi for being a wonderful moderator. And thank you, @BET, for putting together a meaningful discussion! #BecomingOnBET

node.text:
I know there’s a lot going on right now, and it’s easy to feel overwhelmed by the grief coming at us from so many different directions. Yesterday, it was the senseless horror and murder of schoolchildren and educators in Uvalde, Texas. Not long before, it was the hateful murder of Black folks in Buffalo. Today, we remember another trauma, one that’s still with us in so many ways. 

It’s been two years since George Floyd was brutally killed by a police officer. Thinking back to that video and those nine minutes and 29 seconds still shakes so many of us to our core, and it should. 

As we reflect on his murder, and as we mourn those schoolchildren, let’s also remember the millions of people who turned their sadness and anger into activism two years ago. Let’s remember the wave of protests that rattled our consciences. Let’s recommit to the work of change—whether it has to do with how our communities are policed, how our criminal justice system is designed, or how long we’ll continue to accept gun violence as a way of life. 

And most of all, even though it hurts right now, let’s remember that we don’t have to accept any of this as inevitable. So if you feel lost today, hug the ones you love, and do whatever you can to push our country—and the people who lead it—to be a little stronger, braver, and better for all of us.

node.text:
The one and only @Oprah has been such a wonderful friend to me and Barack over the years. That’s why it meant so much to write about her remarkable legacy for #Time100. Here’s what I shared: 

Once, while speaking to a group of college graduates, Oprah said something about her years as an interviewer that struck me. She said, “The common denominator that I found…is we want to be validated. We want to be understood.”

Whether she’s talking to pop stars, Presidents, schoolgirls, scholars—or she’s asking you about your life over a glass of wine in the living room—Oprah has always had that uncanny ability to open us up, to hear beyond our words, and to uncover a higher truth, to be vulnerable with us in a way that allows us to be vulnerable back.

That’s her secret. But what I love most about Oprah is that she has never been content to keep it for herself.

When Oprah connects with something—a person, a book, a song, an idea—she makes sure to shine her light on it. She validates it. She anoints it. People know that when Oprah is involved, there is no pretense, no fluff—whether it’s her work in arts and media or her philanthropic work on health care, food equity, and more.

Every project she touches follows the same pattern, asking us to think critically about our society and how it works, reminding us of our common humanity, and challenging us to take our victories and failures, our pride and vulnerability—and make it all seen.

That’s why no matter where you go, everyone knows her name.

And all of it makes me wonder: maybe her success isn’t rooted in the fact that she found a common denominator that unites us all. Maybe Oprah is our common denominator.

I want to tell you all about something I’m really excited about—it’s called the Voyager Scholarship. I’ve met so many young people who are interested in public service, but are worried about how they’re going to pay for school. They’re wondering how they can afford to go to school while broadening their experiences and seeing the world at the same time. 
 
So Barack and I wanted to help. That’s why we’re thrilled to be teaming up with Airbnb’s Brian Chesky to announce the Voyager Scholarship which will provide financial aid to support their education, expand their horizons, and access an incredible network of leaders and mentors to help young people on their journey to create change. 
 
The Voyager Scholarship is for rising juniors in college in the United States who are committed to making a positive impact—if that sounds like you, I hope you will apply today!

node.text:
It’s been a tough couple of weeks since we saw the leaked SCOTUS draft opinion on abortion. If it comes to pass, we may soon live in a country where millions of women — not to mention our children and grandchildren — lose the right to make decisions about their bodies and their health. Even if we knew the courts were heading toward this day, it doesn’t make the frustration, grief, and fear any less real. 

But we don’t have to stand idly by while others try to turn back the clock on progress. I’m so inspired by everyone out marching today. And I know that we’re going to see so many folks carrying this energy forward to the elections in November and in every election after that. 

And if any of you are questioning whether or not your vote matters, I get it. But state lawmakers are the ones who will determine whether abortion is safe, legal, and accessible in your communities. And we are the ones who determine our state lawmakers. So when you get home from marching, check your voter registration status with @WhenWeAllVote and encourage others to do the same at WhenWeAllVote.org.

Decades before our family lived there, First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt planted a Victory Garden on the White House lawn, and I'm thrilled to share that the Fruit & Vegetable Garden at the Obama Presidential Center will be named in her honor! Mrs. Roosevelt is our longest-serving First Lady, setting a towering standard for so many in our country and around the world, including me. I've always been inspired by her brilliance, her strength, and her remarkable advocacy for the causes she believed in.

The garden itself will be a nod to the White House Kitchen Garden that I planted in 2009, featuring a wide variety of accessible planting beds for seasonal fruits and vegetables. It will also include a picnic area, and Garden Classroom & Teaching Kitchen where visitors of all ages and abilities will be able to participate in hands-on workshops to learn how to grow, harvest, and prepare fresh food. This will be a space for folks on the South Side and visitors alike to come together, and I can’t wait for you all to see it!

Happy College Signing Day! 🎓🥳👏🏾
 
This is one of my favorite days of the year, because nothing brings me more joy than seeing young people committing to their future. For some of you, that starts with going to a community college, a university, or going to school part-time while also working or caring for your family. For others, it’s enlisting in the military or earning a certificate at a trade school to start on your career path.
 
I know that transitions like this are not easy, but I also want you to know that you can do this! You’ve already shown me—and everybody else—what you can do. 
 
To celebrate our eighth annual #CollegeSigningDay, I’m wearing a college shirt from @UMBClife, an Asian American and Native American Pacific Islander Serving Institution in Baltimore County, MD. 

I hope you’ll share your plans for the future with @BetterMakeRoom and me using #CollegeSigningDay. I can’t wait to see all that you do in the years ahead!

From an early age, my mom, Marian Robinson, fostered in me a deep sense of confidence in who I was and who I could be. She taught me how to think for myself, use my own voice, and understand my own worth. I simply wouldn’t be who I am today without her.

As we get ready for #MothersDay, I’m proud to announce that the “Opening the White House” exhibit in the Obama Presidential Center Museum will be named in her honor.

When the museum opens, this will be a place that welcomes folks from across the country and around the world, and thousands of families just like mine who live right down the street. Love you, Mom – thank you for being a guiding light in my life. 💕

node.text:
Happy Teacher Appreciation Week! I heard this story about a teacher in Fremont, California – Ms. Tsung – and had to share it with all of you. Ms. Tsung teaches math, science, and design thinking to 6th graders at Horner Middle School, and has been going above and beyond to think of innovative ways to connect with her students.

The students in her classroom recently had a chance to use the interactive resources from our Pass the Love campaign with @PHAnews on WafflesAndMochi.org to learn about food equity. One of her students, Tevi, shared that this “activity helped me appreciate math because now I see that math can be there in a lot of real-world applications such as starting a business, baking, financial stuff, and more. Waffles + Mochi deal with a lot of math problems each day.”

I couldn't be more thankful for teachers like Ms. Tsung who continue to go above and beyond to inspire and expand their students’ perspectives and experiences. I’d love to hear about an impactful teacher in your life. Share your story with me in the comments!
